My first ML Model using California Housing Prices Dataset¶

1. REPORT DESCRIPTION¶

This report contains trends based on the 1990 California census. The dataset is of houses found in district of California and statistics about it. It was chosen for this report because it is beginner friendly and helpful in understanding the basics of machine learning. This report will show linear regression between the median house value and each of the following independent variables:

  • median income
  • population
  • number of households

Based on the report of comparison between median house value and above 3 variables, we will find which model performs the best in predicting house value.

In [1]:

3.2 DESCRIBE THE VARIABLES¶

Review on these statistics:

The four variables used to plot in this report are median_house value, median_income, population and households. Based on the dataset description, the mean values of the columns fall close to the average value or nearer to the minimum value which says most of the population buy houses that have value from minimum to the average value and very less population buy houses that are worth more.

Column Name Min Max Mean

The only issue is population is high only in some areas and some areas have very less population. So the house value is not evenly distributed among all areas. But still house value hits maximum where there is very less population.

5. MODEL SUMMARY TABLE¶

In [10]:
# Function to return model summary
def run_summary(X, y):
    # Fit the model
    model = LinearRegression().fit(X, y)
    
    # Predict
    y_pred = model.predict(X)
    
    # Calculate metrics
    mse = mean_squared_error(y, y_pred)
    mae = mean_absolute_error(y, y_pred)
    
    # Return model summary
    return {
        'intercept': model.intercept_,
        'slope': model.coef_[0],
        'MSE': mse,
        'MAE': mae,
    }
In [11]:
# Summary 1: Median Income vs. Median House Value
model1_summary = run_summary(housing_data[['median_income']], housing_data['median_house_value'])

# Summary 2: Population vs. Median House Value
model2_summary = run_summary(housing_data[['population']], housing_data['median_house_value'])

# Summary 3: Number of Households vs. Median House Value
model3_summary = run_summary(housing_data[['households']], housing_data['median_house_value'])

7. CONCLUSION¶

Based on the Mean Square Error and Mean Absolute Error obtained, Model 1 (median_house_value vs median_income) predicts better than Model 2 (median_house_value vs population) and Model 3 (median_house_value vs households), since it has smaller values. Model 1 and Model 3 show positive slope, which means that as the median_income and number of households increases respectively, the median_house_value also increases. Whereas, Model 2 shows that as the population increases, median_house_value decreases. The intercepts of Model 1, 2 and 3 give the value of median_house_value when median_income, population and number of households are zero respectively. On the whole, the median income appears to be the most significant predictor of median house values, followed by the number of households, while the population has a less significant impact.
